<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Moral Vegetarianism</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Fri Sep 14, 2018; substantive revision Fri Oct 17, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Billions of humans eat meat. To provide it, we raise animals. We
control, hurt, and kill hundreds of millions of cattle and pigs and
tens of billions of chickens each year.</p>

<p>
To feed these animals, we raise crops. To raise crops, we deforest and
use huge quantities of water. To quench these animals, we use still
more water.</p>

<p>
In turn, these animals produce staggering amounts of waste, waste that
poisons water and soil. These animals produce staggering amounts of
greenhouse gasses.</p>

<p>
To raise these animals and produce this meat, farmers and
slaughterhouse workers labor in conditions from hard to brutal.</p>

<p>
If controlling, hurting, or killing animals is wrong or if the
production of these environmental effects or effects on people is
wrong or if consuming the meat produced is wrong, then a breathtaking
level of meat-related wrong-doing goes on daily.</p>

<p>
Many fewer than a billion humans are vegetarian, have diets excluding
meat. They are vegetarian for various reasons: because it&rsquo;s
healthy, because their parents make them be vegetarian, because they
don&rsquo;t like meat. Porphyry recommended being vegetarian since
eating meat produces pleasure and pleasure is a nail attaching
one&rsquo;s soul to one&rsquo;s body and such attachment interferes
with the intellect&rsquo;s true purpose. Porphyry had other, moral
arguments for vegetarianism, too, and some people are vegetarian on
moral grounds. Moral vegetarianism is the view that it is morally
wrong&mdash;henceforth, &ldquo;wrong&rdquo;&mdash;to eat meat.</p>

<p>
The topic of this entry is moral vegetarianism and the arguments for
it. Strikingly, most contemporary arguments for moral vegetarianism
start with premises about the wrongness of <em>producing</em> meat and
move to conclusions about the wrongness of <em>consuming</em> it. They
do not fasten on some intrinsic feature of meat and insist that
consuming things with that feature is wrong. They do not fasten on
some effect of meat-eating on the eater and insist that producing that
effect is wrong. Rather, they assert that the production of meat is
wrong, that consumption bears a certain relation to production, and
that bearing such a relation to wrongdoing is wrong. So this entry
gives significant space to food production as well as the tricky
business of connecting consumption to production.</p>

<p>
&sect;1 introduces relevant terminology and the main positions
discussed in the entry. &sect;2 explains meat production, the main
moral arguments against it, and some responses to those arguments.
That section&mdash;like the rest of the entry&mdash;homes in on
medium-sized birds and mammals. Yet sea creatures and insects are
killed in a number that dwarfs the number of land animals killed. Some
issues these killings raise are covered in &sect;3.</p>

<p>
None of the foregoing is about consuming animals. &sect;4 covers moral
arguments from premises about meat production to conclusions about
meat consumption. &sect;5 considers some extensions of the arguments
in &sect;2. It speculates about which arguments against meat
production can, if sound, be extended to show that animal product
production or even some plant production is morally wrong. Widespread
discussion of this last idea is relatively new. &sect;6 notes some
other new issues in the moral vegetarian literature.</p>
</div> 

